{"id":"cond-mat/0111085","submitter":"J. M. Speight","authors":"J.M. Speight and P.M. Sutcliffe","title":"Discrete Breathers in Anisotropic Ferromagnetic Spin Chains","comments":"21 pages, 12 figures","journal-ref":"J.Phys.A34:10839-10858,2001","doi":"10.1088/0305-4470/34/49/307","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat hep-th","license":null,"abstract":"  We prove the existence of discrete breathers (time-periodic, spatially\nlocalized solutions) in weakly coupled ferromagnetic spin chains with easy-axis\nanisotropy. Using numerical methods we then investigate the continuation of\ndiscrete breather solutions as the intersite coupling is increased. We find a\nband of frequencies for which the 1-site breather continues all the way to the\nsoliton solution in the continuum. There is a second band, which abuts the\nfirst, in which the 1-site breather does not continue to the soliton solution,\nbut a certain multi-site breather does. This banded structure continues, so\nthat in each band there is a particular multi-site breather which continues to\nthe soliton solution. A detailed analysis is presented, including an exposition\nof how the bifurcation pattern changes as a band is crossed. The linear\nstability of breathers is analyzed. It is proved that 1-site breathers are\nstable at small coupling, provided a non-resonance condition holds, and an\nextensive numerical stability analysis of 1-site and multisite breathers is\nperformed. The results show alternating bands of stability and instability as\nthe coupling increases.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 6 Nov 2001 13:25:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-11-26"}
